Not very likely, I'll admit.  Idaho is both a small state and a reliably
Republican one, and Craig was never among the most famous of Senators
(until recently...).

Still:  let's assume that Colin Powell decides to run in 1996 and gets the
Republican presidential nomination.  (It may be objected that he was just
too liberal to get the nomination, but some conservatives--though mostly
&quot;national greatness&quot; conservatives of the Weekly Standard type--were
booming him, arguing that he was the only Republican who could win.  Given
his personal popularity, the &quot;electability&quot; argument, and the fact that
the vote to the right of him will be divided among several candidates,
Powelll's nomination is possible.  Moroever, one might also see an
unusually large cross-over of black voters into the Republican primaries,
especially since there is no significant challenge to Clinton among the
Democrats.)  Powell, as a Northeasterner whose liberal views on social
issues make many Republicans uneasy, feels he has to balance the ticket
with a Western conservative--yet he doesn't want one who is so well-known
or popular among conservatives that he will have an indpendent power base
as vice-president and potentially be a rival to Powell.  Craig is
sufficiently conservative, sufficiently Western, and sufficiently obscure.

Powell beats Clinton?  Conceivable, since even Dole came within eight
points--which means you just have to change the minds of four percent of
the voters.  (Although it is true that Powell might have to face a right-
wing third party.)  Anyway, once the Powell-Craig ticket is elected, the
usual (well, usual in alternate history, anyway) assassination or accident
occurs....

