Well...maybe not.  I mean, look at the timing.  Let's say (handwave)
Powell-Craig is elected in '96.  That takes them through the Kosovo
War (and what an interesting set of discussions *that* is going to be
in a Powell Administration...) and the bursting of the Internet Bubble
Economy.  Then the kicker:  9-11.

I can see Powell-Craig winning in '00, the recession hitting (really,
nothing was going to stop that and I'm presuming Powell ends up
renominating Greenspan anyway) and that, plus 9-11 causing a
significant problem for the Administration.  Depending on what he does
after 9-11, how America responds, things could smoothly pave the way
for the Veep getting an easy '04 win *OR* a debacle at the polls.

There's a *lot* of issues here that would need to be settled out,
going as far back as Kosovo.

1.  Does Washington press NATO to intervene in Kosovo?

Problem here is that Powell has a very clear record on this type of
thing:  all or nothing.  If you're going to get into a fight, go in
with everything and slay everything on the ground.  Remember the First
Gulf War.  I *still* get the chills when I hear him say &quot;First we're
going to cut it off and then we're going to kill it.&quot;  If--and that's
a big if--he follows that line of thinking, Kosovo could've turned
into a more conventional war, with heavy emphasis on Gulf War-styled
armoured thrusts into Serbia.  Not that the notion of bombing Belgrade
into the Stone Age wouldn't've appealed but if he were going to go in,
the *LAST* thing he would've done was telegraph that there would be no
ground campaign.  Consequently, the timetable for using ground troops
would've been significantly shorter and more organic to the decision-
making, not tacked on when NATO realised Slobo wasn't going to roll
over and play dead.

Prediction:  A quick, Gulf War-styled Kosovo War.  Air campaign
followed by ground campaign, culminating in a decisive victory which
fissures off Kosovo from Serbia.  No UNMIK in the traditional sense.
Kosovo was destined for independence in this scenario with none of the
footsie-playing we've got going on now.  Consequently, NATO's
reputation is *solidified*.  They don't look like a bunch of guys who
pulled a victory out of a disaster anymore.  The Alliance looks and
acts more robust.  No kowtowing to Paris, frex (no way Powell is going
to let Paris make targetting decisions like Clinton did).

Secondary Prediction:  Earlier disillusionment between Moscow,
Brussels and Washington.  No one really knew where Moscow was heading
in those heady days.  Things took a turn for the worse when Yeltsin
tried to make an end-run around the Alliance in the closing days of
Kosovo.  That would not have happened under Powell, who would've
warned Yeltsin off and probably would have assumed a foreign policy
closer to Bush I, treating Russia as a Little Soviet Union until they
proved themselves something different, with all that entails.  Yeltsin
might *still* try something like that, but Powell's not likely to back
down and when/if Wes Clark is faced with Russian troops heading to
Prestina...could get dicey.  But Boris isn't going to start a
conflict, so he'll back down...grumbling.  The EU sees this and
perhaps realises that maybe things haven't changed all that much back
in Moscow, especially if it's seen that Russia is clearly supporting a
genocidal Serbia and wants to undo a very successful war against
Belgrade.

2.  Washington's Reaction to AQ Before 9-11?

More robust than OTL Clinton II?  I'm not sure.  But when the USS COLE
is bombed, I can almost guarantee some kind of action.  There's going
to be none of this fiddling around, treating it like a criminal case.
That might send a serious wake-up call through the White House.  Might
there already be a low-key anti-terrorist campaign going on prior to
9-11?  Perhaps.  Delta Force?  CIA squads?  If any of the above
happens, that might change the timeline of 9-11 but I don't think
that's the case, unless one posits a really, serious change of
attitude.  Frankly, all parties seemed to be very quiescent and
dismissive about the possibility of a large-scale terror attack in the
US.

3.  9-11

Okay, what happens?  We know that in OTL, the neoconservatives
immediately leapt on the Iraqis, wanting to take out every possible
threat that could be managed, using 9-11 as a broad justification.
But they're not likely to be in positions of power on that day.  A
Powell Administration will be a technocratic one, more Bush I than
Bush II.  What happens then?  Definitely no Iraq campaign but there
might be an actually LARGER Afghanistan one.

Again, using the Gulf War and Kosovo as templates, the US is going to
attempt what unmanned the Soviets:  a full-scale, balls-to-the-wall,
land invasion.  What might also be different here is the posibility of
a NATO role.  In OTL, support was limited, though everything was on
the table.  Same situation here, although with a successful Kosovo
War, who's to say that Powell doesn't ask NATO for a more substantial
contribution, making it the second full-scale NATO war in less than a
decade?

So...going into '04, we've got NATO fully engaged in Kosovo and
Afghanistan (maybe Pakistan and Somalia as well, on the assumption
that AQ flees to the former and latter after they get hammered in
Afghanistan).  The economy?  That's the big question mark here.  Could
be in bad shape, depending on what Greenspan does, how the markets
whether the war, the price of oil...you name it.  Very, very fluid
here.

'04 might not be a push-over for Craig.

Thorgrim
