That was the question I asked as well.  My thought is, having fought the
Gulf War and then replicated the pattern in the *Kosovo War, the
temptation would be there to do the same in Afghanistan and damn the New
York Times and Johnny Apple's defeatism.

And why not?  Just because the British and the Soviets couldn't handle
Afghanistan is one thing.  But a combined NATO operation?  That's a
whole 'nuther ball game, with totally different ways to fight involved,
to say nothing of motivations.  It's not a matter of imperial yearnings;
it's pure and simple revenge.  One will fight for king and country but
it's probably axiomatic that it's easier to *die* for king and country
knowing that your cause is *just*.  From America's perspective, there
couldn't've been a more clear-cut case of 'just war' than Afghanistan
