Not necessarily the case and it presumes a misunderstanding of how
American--to say nothing of NATO--forces are trained to fight.  So-
called 'collateral damage' (I could pop the cynical bastard who came up
with that term) is inevitable but for at least the last twenty years, US
forces--and through them NATO forces--have been trained to minimise it
to the greatest extent possible.  You'd be amazed at how meticulous the
targeteering and mensuration process is.  It's not infallible but it's
far and away from the mess that existed prior to the '80s or even the
early '90s.

Besides, Afghanistan isn't suited to, say, large armoured cav incursions
save in very few areas.  Mobility would have always had to've been the
watchword in any military move there.  The difference wasn't between
&quot;Should we send in the armoured cav or should we send in the 82nd
Airborn?&quot; but &quot;How *much* of the 82nd should we send and what *other*
mobile forces should go with 'em?&quot;.  The same folks who manned the Fulda
Gap weren't going to Afghanistan.

A semi-conventional campaign which included heavily NATO input might
well have been swifter and may, just may have gotten bin Laden...or
maybe not.  Slippery li'l bugger, he is.  But in any case, with more
troops on the ground and a greater international input, pacification,
reconstruction and reconciliation could've taken a huge step forward
vice the series of interminable tiny ones that led up to where we are
now.  The end result might have been to stabilise Afghanistan quicker
though how &quot;solid&quot; this stability is is anyone's guess.

