imagine him telling Musharraf in no uncertain terms what is to be
expected of Islamabad, noting that the US saved Pakistan from being
humiliated yet again as early as the Kargil War not a couple years
earlier (which reminds me, how would a Powell Administration approach
*that* little flareup?).

Besides, the Allies have a pretty good idea where Pakistan keeps its
weapons, launchers and knows precisely what Islamabad's doctrine is for
their usage.  Should everything go pear-shaped, AQ spill over into
Pakistan-proper--not just the tribal reserves--and a required incursion
is needed, the very first thing that's going to occur is a snatch n'
grab operation.  The first anyone will hear of it will be after it's all
over and the weapons are either secured or destroyed.  Pakistan is of no
threat to anyone but herself in the end.  And the US in OTL made it
perfectly clear where *anyone* stood in this war:  for or against us.
There would be no 'neutrals'.  Hence, Islamabad's cooperation.  I cannot
imagine Colin Powell doing less than that.  Quite possibly--and oddly,
considering how passive the doctrine which bears his name is--he's
liable to be even *more* bellicose on that point, simply by the virtue
of his past history as Chairman of the Joint Chiefs.  Nations
*implicitly* will realise he's liable to think in military terms and
