I have some real doubts about the meaning of those exit survey
numbers.  There is some evidence that minority candidates suffer from
a social desirability penalty in surveys of voting intentions.  The
percentage of voters who _say_ they will vote for a minority candidate
tends to be higher than the percentage of votes that candidate then
gets in the election.  A quick Google produced a couple of citations
along these lines (Race-of-Interviewer Effects in a Preelection Poll:
Virginia 1989 Steven E. Finkel, Thomas M. Guterbock, Marian Ja. Borg
The Public Opinion Quarterly, Vol. 55, No. 3 (Autumn, 1991), pp.
313-330; When White Voters Evaluate Black Candidates: The Processing
Implications of Candidate Skin Color, Prejudice, and Self-Monitoring
Nayda Terkildsen, American Journal of Political Science, Vol. 37, No.
4 (Nov., 1993), pp. 1032-1053).

Furthermore that three-way Powell, Clinton, Perot split assumes that
the Republicans, after working on Nixon's Southern Strategy for over
20 years, would (a) run a very non-Southern Strategy candidate and (b)
that doing so wouldn't splinter the modern GOP coalition.

